   230	Common CLI across all three:
   231	
   232	- `--task-store-url URL`.
   233	- `--experiment-id ID`.
   234	- `--shared-token TOKEN`.
   235	- `--worker-id ID` — required. Distinct per-process identifier.
   236	- `--poll-interval SECONDS` — default `0.1`.
   237	- `--startup-timeout SECONDS` — default `30`.
   238	- `--log-level LEVEL`.
   239	
   240	Role-specific args:
   241	
   242	- Planner: `--base-commit-sha HEX` (required) + `--proposals-per-plan N`
   243	  (default `1`). The fixed `plan_fn` emits proposals with
   244	  `parent_commits=(base_commit_sha,)`.
   245	- Implementer: `--repo-path PATH` (required) + `--fail-every N`
   246	  (optional, default never). See "Implementer repo model" above.
   247	  (The implementer reads parents from the proposal; no
   248	  `--base-commit-sha` flag.)
   249	- Evaluator: `--experiment-config PATH` (required, to know the
   250	  metrics schema and emit matching keys) + `--fail-every N`
   251	  (optional).
   252	
   253	Startup: readiness probe, construct `StoreClient`, construct
   254	`ScriptedPlanner` / `ScriptedImplementer` / `ScriptedEvaluator` with
   255	the existing scripted `plan_fn` / `implement_fn` / `evaluate_fn` (see
   256	"Scripted logic" below). Loop: `run_pending(client)`; if it returned 0,
   257	sleep `--poll-interval`; else loop again immediately (drain bursts
   258	without sleeping).
   259	
   260	Workers never self-terminate on empty work. They exit on SIGTERM
   261	only. This matches the Phase 9 UI-driven model too — a worker's
   262	lifecycle is owned by its supervisor, not by task availability.
   263	
   264	**Scripted logic across the subprocess boundary.** Today
   265	`ScriptedPlanner` / `ScriptedImplementer` / `ScriptedEvaluator` take
   266	user-supplied Python callables (`plan_fn`, `implement_fn`,
   267	`evaluate_fn`) at construction. That arrangement does not survive
   268	being put behind a CLI — Python callables don't cross a
   269	`python -m eden_planner_host …` boundary.
   270	
   271	8b resolves this by **baking one built-in profile into each worker
   272	host**. A new module `reference/services/_common/scripted.py` owns
   273	the canonical 8b profile: the same deterministic "3 trials, all
   274	succeed" shape the Phase 5 / 7b in-process tests use today, with a
   275	couple of knobs configurable via CLI rather than by injecting a
   276	function:
   277	
   278	- Planner host: fixed `plan_fn` that drafts `--proposals-per-plan`
   279	  proposals per task (default `1`) with deterministic slugs derived
   280	  from the plan task ID. Each proposal's `parent_commits` is
   281	  `(base_commit_sha,)`, where `base_commit_sha` is read from the
   282	  `--base-commit-sha HEX` CLI flag. (Proposals MUST carry ≥1 parent
   283	  per [`02-data-model.md`](../../spec/v0/02-data-model.md) §5;
   284	  threading a concrete SHA through boot-time config is the cleanest
   285	  way to satisfy that without giving the planner repo access.)
   286	- Implementer host: fixed `implement_fn` that writes a real git
   287	  commit to the shared bare repo (see "Implementer repo model"
   288	  below) and returns its SHA. `--fail-every N` (default: never
   289	  fail) flips occasional trials to `status=error` to exercise
   290	  rejection paths in tests.
   291	- Evaluator host: fixed `evaluate_fn` that returns scripted metrics
   292	  matching the experiment's `metrics_schema` (read from
   293	  `--experiment-config` so the evaluator knows what keys to emit).
   294	  `--fail-every N` flips occasional evaluations to
   295	  `status=error` / `status=eval_error` if a test wants them.
   296	
   297	The `ScriptedPlanner` / `ScriptedImplementer` / `ScriptedEvaluator`
   298	classes stay callable-injected for Phase 5 / 7b in-process tests —
   299	the worker hosts are the only callers that wrap them in the fixed
   300	profile. This way nothing about the in-process test surface changes.
   301	
   302	Selector: a `--profile NAME` CLI flag is **not** introduced in 8b —
   303	the fixed profile is the only option. When real LLM-backed workers
   304	land (Phase 10 LLM hosts), they ship as separate worker hosts
   305	(`eden_llm_planner_host`, etc.) rather than as a `--profile llm`
   306	switch on the scripted host. Keeping the split explicit at the
   307	binary level means the scripted and LLM hosts don't share
   308	configuration surfaces that each only half-understands.
   309	
   310	**Implementer repo model.** The `Integrator` requires that the
   311	`commit_sha` an implementer submits be a real, reachable commit on
   312	a branch it can read
   313	([integrator.py](../../reference/packages/eden-git/src/eden_git/integrator.py) §2
   314	preconditions). Today's Phase 7b E2E fixture satisfies this by
   315	prebuilding real `work/*` branches before running the experiment
   316	and returning those real SHAs from the scripted `implement_fn`.
   317	Phase 8b needs the equivalent inside a standalone process.
   318	
   319	Decision: the implementer host writes real commits directly, via a
   320	`GitRepo` opened against the **same bare repo** the orchestrator's
   321	`Integrator` reads from.
   322	
   323	- Implementer CLI gains `--repo-path PATH` — the bare repo it
   324	  writes to. Same path the orchestrator passes to `--repo-path`.
   325	- Implementer's scripted flow per task builds a real commit whose
   326	  parent is the SHA the proposal named:
   327	  1. Read `proposal.parent_commits` from the store — guaranteed
   328	     non-empty by the proposal Pydantic binding's
   329	     `min_length=1` constraint. The scripted planner's fixed
   330	     profile always emits a single parent, so the implementer's
   331	     scripted profile uses `proposal.parent_commits[0]` as the
   332	     single commit parent. (A non-scripted future implementer
   333	     could honor multi-parent proposals as merge commits;
   334	     scripted 8b does not.)
   335	  2. Build a tree containing one deterministic blob (filename
   336	     derived from the proposal slug, content derived from the
   337	     trial ID) via `GitRepo.write_blob` +
   338	     `write_tree_from_entries`.
   339	  3. `commit_tree` with that tree, `parent=parent_sha` from step
   340	     1, fixed author / committer identity, deterministic message
   341	     derived from the proposal slug + trial ID.
   342	  4. `create_ref refs/heads/work/<slug>-<trial_id>` → new SHA.
   343	  5. Submit the new SHA on the implement task.
   344	
   345	  Because the proposal's `parent_commits` is populated and the
   346	  implementer's new commit descends from it, the Integrator's §1.4
   347	  reachability check (each `trial.parent_commits[i]` must be
   348	  reachable from `commit_sha`) and its §2 check (`commit_sha` is
   349	  reachable from `branch` tip) both hold.
   350	
   351	- **Seed commit.** The test harness seeds the bare repo with an
   352	  empty initial commit before boot and passes its SHA to the
   353	  planner and implementer as `--base-commit-sha`. (The orchestrator
   354	  does not need the SHA — it only reads what the store already
   355	  records.) Seeding is a tiny helper in `reference/services/_common/`
   356	  (`seed_bare_repo(path) -> str`) so service tests can reuse it.
   357	
   358	This keeps the implementer host's write path identical to how the
   359	Phase 7b test prebuilds branches, just inside the service loop
   360	rather than in a test fixture. Concurrency is fine: worker hosts
   361	only write `work/*` refs; the orchestrator's `Integrator` only
   362	writes `trial/*` refs and reads `work/*` refs. Git's packed-refs +
   363	loose-refs arrangement is safe under concurrent writers in
   364	distinct ref namespaces.
   365	
   366	**ID allocation across restarts.** Counter-based prefixes
   367	(`proposal-1`, `proposal-2`, …) collide on restart because a fresh
   368	worker has no knowledge of persisted state. Decision: worker-
   369	generated IDs (`proposal_id`, `trial_id`) are short UUIDv4 hex
   370	strings prefixed by a role tag — `proposal-<uuid>`, `trial-<uuid>`.
   371	The `--proposal-prefix` / `--trial-prefix` flags are dropped; the
   372	orchestrator-allocated task IDs keep `--implement-task-prefix` /
   373	`--evaluate-task-prefix` (because those are used for human-readable
   374	IDs in logs and E2E assertions), but the per-iteration uniqueness
   375	comes from appending a short UUID.
   376	
   377	The E2E test asserts on the *count* and *shape* of produced IDs,
   378	not specific values — so UUIDs are fine. Plan task IDs remain
   379	explicit (`--plan-tasks plan-1,plan-2,plan-3`) because the harness
   380	needs to reference them in assertions.

